==English==

===Etymology===
French ''[[accréditer]]''; ''à'' (Latin ''[[ad]]'') + ''[[crédit]]'' credit. See [[credit]].

===Pronunciation===
'''ac-cre*dit'''
* {{IPA|/əˈkrɛdɪt/}}
* {{audio|en-us-accredit.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive}} To put or bring into [[credit]]; to [[invest]] with credit or [[authority]]; to [[sanction]].
#:* His censure will ... '''accredit''' his praises. - [[w:William Cowper|William Cowper]]
#:* These reasons ... which '''accredit''' and fortify mine opinion. - [[w:Thomas Shelton|Thomas Shelton]]
# {{transitive}} To send with [[letter]]s [[credential]], as an [[ambassador]], [[envoy]], or [[diplomatic]] agent; to [[authorize]], as a [[messenger]] or [[delegate]].
#:* Beton ... was '''accredited''' to the Court of France. - [[w:James Anthony Froude|James Anthony Froude]]
# {{transitive}} To [[believe]]; to [[credit]]; to put trust in.
#:* The version of early Roman history which was '''accredited''' in the fifth century. - [[w:G. C. Lewis|G. C. Lewis]]
#:* He '''accredited''' and repeated stories of apparitions and witchcraft. - [[w:Robert Southey|Robert Southey]]
# {{transitive}} To credit; to [[vouch]] for or consider (some one) as doing something, or (something) as belonging to some one; as '''To accredit''' (one) '''with''' (something), to [[attribute]] something to him; as, Mr. Clay was '''accredited with''' these views; they '''accredit''' him '''with''' a wise saying.

